T1  - BUBBLES, CRASHES, AND ENDOGENOUS UNCERTAINTY IN LINKED ASSET AND PRODUCT MARKETS*
AU  - Jaworski, Taylor
AU  - Kimbrough, Erik O.
Y1  - 2016/02/01
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12151
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 155
EP  - 176
VL  - 57
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12151
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In laboratory asset markets, subjects trade shares of a firm whose profits in a linked product market determine dividends. Treatments vary whether dividend information is revealed once per period or in real time and whether the firm is controlled by a profit-maximizing robot or human subject. The latter variation induces uncertainty about firm behavior, bridging the gap between laboratory and field markets. Our data replicate well-known features of laboratory asset markets (e.g., bubbles), suggesting these are robust to a market-based dividend process. Compared to a sample of previous experiments, both real-time information revelation and endogenous uncertainty impede the bubble-mitigating impact of experience.
ER  - 

