T1  - MONETARY POLICY REGIME SWITCHES AND MACROECONOMIC DYNAMICS*
AU  - Foerster, Andrew T.
Y1  - 2016/02/01
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12153
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 211
EP  - 230
VL  - 57
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12153
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article considers the determinacy and distributional consequences of regime switching in monetary policy. Although switching in the inflation target does not affect determinacy, switches in the inflation response can cause indeterminacy. Satisfying the Taylor principle period by period is neither necessary nor sufficient for determinacy when inflation responses switch; indeterminacy can arise if monetary policy responds too aggressively to inflation in the active regime. Inflation target switches primarily impact the level of inflation, whereas inflation response switches primarily impact the volatility. Expecting an inflation target switch has minor effects on volatility, whereas expecting an inflation response switch raises volatility more substantially.
ER  - 

